"Saxon E., Baker B., Hargrove W., Hoffman F., Zganjar C.","Mapping environments at risk under different global climate change scenarios",2005,"Ecology Letters","8","1",,"53","60",,,10.1111/j.1461-0248.2004.00694.x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-12944265106&partnerID=40&md5=7e4c3f210899f42bc9a44ff5a7e51b20","TNC-CI Jt. Initiative Climate C., 1919 M St. NW, Washington, DC 20036, United States; TNC-CI Jt. Initiative Climate C., 2424 Spruce St., Boulder, CO 80302, United States; Environmental Sciences Division, Oak Ridge National Laboratory, M. S. 6407, PO Box 2008, Oak Ridge, TN 37830, United States","Saxon, E., TNC-CI Jt. Initiative Climate C., 1919 M St. NW, Washington, DC 20036, United States; Baker, B., TNC-CI Jt. Initiative Climate C., 2424 Spruce St., Boulder, CO 80302, United States; Hargrove, W., Environmental Sciences Division, Oak Ridge National Laboratory, M. S. 6407, PO Box 2008, Oak Ridge, TN 37830, United States; Hoffman, F., Environmental Sciences Division, Oak Ridge National Laboratory, M. S. 6407, PO Box 2008, Oak Ridge, TN 37830, United States; Zganjar, C., TNC-CI Jt. Initiative Climate C., 1919 M St. NW, Washington, DC 20036, United States","All global circulation models based on Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) scenarios project profound changes, but there is no consensus on how to map their environmental consequences. Our multivariate representation of environmental space combines stable topographic and edaphic attributes with dynamic climatic attributes. We divide that environmental space into 500 unique domains and map their current locations and their projected locations in 2100 under contrasting emissions scenarios. The environmental domains found across half the study area today disappear under the higher emissions scenario, but persist somewhere in it under the lower emissions scenario. Locations affected least and those affected most under each scenario are mapped. This provides an explicit framework for designing conservation networks to include both areas at least risk (potential refugia) and areas at greatest risk, where novel communities may form and where sentinel ecosystems can be monitored for signs of stress.","Biodiversity conservation; Climate change; Domains; Ecoregions; Mapping; Multivariate cluster analysis; Scenarios","climate change; conservation; environmental risk; global change; mapping",,,,,,"Bailey, R., (1996) Ecosystem Geography, , Springer, New York, NY; Daly, C., Gibson, W.P., Taylor, G.H., Johnson, G.L., Pasteris, P., A knowledge-based approach to the statistical mapping of climate (2002) Clim. Res., 22, pp. 99-113; Faith, D.P., Walker, P.A., Environmental diversity: On the best possible use of surrogate data for assessing the relative biodiversity of a set of areas (1996) Biodiv. Conserv., 5, pp. 431-446; (2000) Global Gridded Surfaces of Selected Soil Characteristics (International Geosphere-Biosphere Programme - Data and Information System) Data Set, , http://www.daac.ornl.gov, Oak Ridge National Laboratory Distributed Active Archive Center, Oak Ridge, TN, USA; Gordon, C., Cooper, C., Senior, C.A., Banks, H., Gregory, J.M., Johns, T.C., The simulation of SST, sea ice extents and ocean heat transports in a version of the Hadley Centre coupled model without flux adjustments (2000) Clim. Dyn., 16, pp. 123-146; Groves, C.R., (2003) Drafting a Conservation Blueprint: A Practitioner's Guide to Planning for Biodiversity, , Island Press, Washington, DC; Hargrove, W.H., Hoffman, F.M., The potential of multivariate quantitative methods for computation and visualization of ecoregions (2005) Environ. Manage., Special Edition, , in press; Iverson, L.R., Prasad, A., Schwartz, M.W., Modeling potential future individual tree-species distributions in the eastern United States under a climate change scenario: A case study with Pinus virginiana (1999) Ecol. Model., 115, pp. 77-93; Malcolm, J.R., Markham, A., (2000) Global Warning and Terrestrial Biodiversity Decline, , World Wide Fund Nat., Gland; Mitchell, T.D., Carter, T.R., Jones, P.D., Hulme, M., New, M., (2003) A Comprehensive Set of High-resolution Grids of Monthly Climate for Europe and the Globe: The Observed Record (1901-2000) and 16 Scenarios (2001-2100), , http://www.cru.uea.ac.uk/~timm/data/index.html; Nakicenovic, N., Swart, R., (2000) Emissions Scenarios: A Special Report of Working Group III of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, , Cambridge University Press, Cambridge; Olsen, D.M., Dinerstein, E., The Global 200: A representative approach to conserving the Earth's most biologically valuable ecoregions (1998) Cons. Biol., 12, pp. 502-515; Overpeck, J.T., Webb, R.S., Webb, T., Mapping eastern North American vegetation change of the past 18,000 years: No-analogs and the future (1992) Geology, 20, pp. 1071-1074; Peterson, A.T., Ortega-Huetta, M.A., Bartley, J., Sanchez-Cordero, V., Soberon, J., Buddemeier, R.H., Future projections for Mexican faunas under global climate change scenarios (2002) Nature, 416, pp. 626-629; Pielke, R.E., Avissar, R., Raupach, M., Dolman, A.J., Zeng, X.B., Denning, A.S., Interactions between the atmosphere and terrestrial ecosystems: Influence on weather and climate (1998) Global Change Biol., 4, pp. 461-475; Pope, V.D., Gallani, M.L., Rowntree, P.R., Stratton, A., The impact of new physical parameterizations in the Hadley Centre climate model - HadCM3 (2000) Clim. Dyn., 16, pp. 123-146; Rupp, T.S., Chapin III, F.S., Starfield, A.M., Modeling the influence of topographic barriers on treeline advance at the forest-tundra ecotone in northwestern Alaska (2001) Clim. Change, 48, pp. 399-416; Saxon, E.C., Adapting ecoregional plans to anticipate the impact of climate change, Chapter 12 (2003) Drafting a Conservation Blueprint: A Practitioner's Guide to Planning for Biodiversity, pp. 345-365. , (ed. Groves, C.R.). Island Press, Washington, DC; Sitch, S., Smith, B., Prentice, I.C., Arneth, A., Bondeau, A., Cramer, W., Evaluat